## SETUP

- Run Postgres and Redis via Docker
``` docker compose up -d ```

- Install dependencies
```
npm i
```

- Create a `.env` file like the example below

```
PORT=3000

DATABASE_URL="postgresql://johndoe:randompassword@localhost:5432/mydb?schema=public"

REDIS_HOST=localhost
REDIS_PORT=6379
```

- Migrate and seed database

```
npx prisma db migrate reset
```

- Run the dev server (both NestJS API and Next.js frontend on the same port)
```
npm run start:dev
```

The application runs on a single port (default 3000):
- Next.js pages are served at `/`, `/users`, `/about`, etc.
- NestJS API endpoints are available at `/api/users`, `/api`, etc.

## NOTES

- Both Next.js frontend and NestJS backend run in the same Node.js instance
- API routes are prefixed with `/api` (e.g., `/api/users`)
- e2e tests using Playwright to guarantee integration between frontend and backend
- Backend tests using @nestjs/testing which uses Jest under the hood
